    rank: 85,
    name: "Terlipressin",
    slug: "terlipressin",
    category: "Cardiovascular",
    aliases: ["Terlivaz","Glypressin","Terlipressin Acetate","Triglycyl Lysine Vasopressin"],
    shortDescription: "A synthetic vasopressin analog that selectively targets V1 receptors to reduce splanchnic blood flow, FDA-approved for the treatment of hepatorenal syndrome with rapid reduction in renal failure.",
    fullDescription: `Terlipressin is a synthetic analog of vasopressin consisting of lysine vasopressin with a triglycyl modification at the N-terminus. This modification acts as a prodrug mechanism — the triglycyl residues are slowly cleaved by endopeptidases in the bloodstream, gradually releasing active lysine vasopressin. This slow conversion provides sustained pharmacological activity with a more stable pharmacokinetic profile than native vasopressin, allowing bolus intravenous dosing rather than continuous infusion.

Terlipressin preferentially activates vasopressin V1 receptors over V2 receptors, producing selective vasoconstriction of the splanchnic vascular bed. This reduces portal venous pressure and blood flow to varices while also increasing renal perfusion pressure through systemic vasoconstriction. In the kidneys, this results in improved renal blood flow and glomerular filtration rate, which is the basis for its use in hepatorenal syndrome (HRS).

In September 2022, terlipressin was approved by the FDA (marketed as Terlivaz) for the treatment of hepatorenal syndrome type 1 (HRS-1) — now termed HRS-acute kidney injury (HRS-AKI) — in adults. The CONFIRM trial demonstrated that terlipressin significantly improved renal function (as measured by the primary endpoint of verified HRS reversal) compared to placebo when used with albumin. HRS is a devastating complication of advanced liver disease with high mortality, and terlipressin represents the first FDA-approved pharmacotherapy for this condition.

Outside the United States, terlipressin has been used for decades for the management of acute variceal bleeding, where it reduces portal pressure and helps control hemorrhage. It has also been studied for septic shock as a vasopressor alternative, particularly in vasopressin-resistant or catecholamine-resistant shock states.`,
    uses: ["FDA-approved treatment of hepatorenal syndrome type 1 (HRS-AKI) in adults","Acute management of esophageal variceal bleeding (standard of care in many countries outside US)","Splanchnic vasoconstriction to reduce portal hypertension","Investigated as a vasopressor in septic shock","Research into vasopressin receptor-selective pharmacology","Treatment of type 2 HRS (off-label)"],
    researchFindings: ["The CONFIRM trial demonstrated verified HRS reversal in 32% of terlipressin-treated patients versus 17% with placebo in HRS type 1 (NEJM, 2021).","Meta-analyses of variceal bleeding trials showed terlipressin reduces failure to control bleeding and mortality compared to placebo.","Studies showed terlipressin improves renal function parameters (creatinine, urine output) in approximately 40-50% of HRS patients when combined with albumin.","Research confirmed terlipressin has approximately 3-fold selectivity for V1 over V2 receptors, explaining its hemodynamic rather than antidiuretic predominance.","Comparative studies suggested terlipressin is more effective than midodrine/octreotide combination for HRS reversal."],
    risks: ["Serious respiratory failure, including ARDS-like presentations, reported in clinical trials; carries a boxed warning.","Abdominal cramps, diarrhea, and nausea are common.","Peripheral and cardiac ischemia risk due to vasoconstriction; contraindicated in patients with coronary or peripheral artery disease.","Hyponatremia due to some V2 receptor activation causing water retention.","Skin necrosis at peripheral sites reported rarely with vasoconstrictive effects."],
    administration: "For HRS: 0.85 mg IV bolus every 6 hours. Dose may be increased to 1.7 mg every 6 hours if serum creatinine has not decreased by at least 30% by day 4. Maximum treatment duration 14 days. Administered only in hospital ICU settings with close hemodynamic and respiratory monitoring. For variceal bleeding (outside US): 2 mg IV bolus followed by 1-2 mg every 4-6 hours for up to 5 days.",
    legalStatus: "FDA-approved in 2022 (marketed as Terlivaz) for hepatorenal syndrome. Approved in many countries outside the US (as Glypressin) for variceal bleeding. Available in hospital settings only by prescription. Not a controlled substance.",
